INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '98b68397-5974-4a00-ad63-404d60010d74',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana's Three Pillars — Why Loki, Mimir, and Tempo Only Work Together$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana's observability stack maps each pillar to a dedicated store, but they compound only when correlated.

Metrics (Prometheus/Mimir + PromQL) answer is something wrong? histogram_quantile(0.99, rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m])) spikes — you get an alert. Fast, cheap, but dimensionless. You know latency degraded; you don't know why.

Logs (Loki + LogQL) answer what happened? Structured filtering via | json, | pattern, and label_format lets you isolate error events by service, pod, or user. LogQL's count_over_time even bridges into metrics space — but raw logs without a trace ID are grep archaeology.

Traces (Tempo + TraceQL) answer where in the call graph? {duration > 500ms && resource.service.name = "checkout"} pinpoints slow spans across services in a single query.

Grafana's glue closes the loop: derived fields in the Loki datasource config extract trace_id from log lines and deep-link directly into Tempo's trace view. Prometheus exemplars embed trace IDs inside metric scrapes. In Grafana Explore, you pivot from a PromQL anomaly to correlated Loki logs to the exact Tempo trace — one browser tab, no context switch. That's what compresses MTTR from minutes to seconds.$escape$,
  $escape$# Loki datasource provisioning — derived field links log trace_id → Tempo
apiVersion: 1
datasources:
  - name: Loki
    type: loki
    url: http://loki:3100
    jsonData:
      derivedFields:
        - name: TraceID
          matcherRegex: 'trace_id=(\w+)'
          url: '${__value.raw}'
          datasourceUid: tempo
          urlDisplayLabel: Open in Tempo
  - name: Tempo
    type: tempo
    uid: tempo
    url: http://tempo:3200
    jsonData:
      tracesToLogsV2:
        datasourceUid: loki
        filterByTraceID: true$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
