INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'af6ce8cb-0013-4bd0-890d-5f461569bedd',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana + Prometheus — Recording Rules, PromQL, and Alert Evaluation in Practice$escape$,
  $escape$Prometheus stores metrics as time series identified by a metric name and key-value labels. Four types matter: counters (monotonically increasing), gauges (point-in-time values), histograms (bucketed observations), and summaries. Grafana's Prometheus data source sends PromQL at every panel refresh — expensive for high-cardinality expressions over long retention windows.

Recording rules solve this. Defined in Prometheus `rule_files`, they precompute heavy expressions into new series on a fixed interval. In Grafana dashboards, replace raw expressions like `rate(http_requests_total[5m])` with the recorded series `job:http_requests:rate5m` — panel load time drops significantly, and the series is also indexable in Explore.

Alerting rules share the same YAML group structure. When using Grafana Mimir or Cortex as your backend, Grafana's built-in ruler evaluates these rules directly — no separate Prometheus instance needed. The `for` duration prevents flapping by requiring the condition to hold continuously. Use `{{ $value | humanizePercentage }}` in `annotations` to embed live metric values in Grafana notification templates, and `labels` to control Alertmanager routing trees.$escape$,
  $escape$groups:
  - name: http_metrics
    interval: 1m
    rules:
      - record: job:http_requests:rate5m
        expr: sum by (job) (rate(http_requests_total[5m]))

      - alert: HighErrorRate
        expr: |
          sum by (job) (rate(http_requests_total{status=~"5.."}[5m]))
          /
          sum by (job) (rate(http_requests_total[5m])) > 0.05
        for: 2m
        labels:
          severity: critical
        annotations:
          summary: "{{ $labels.job }} error rate {{ $value | humanizePercentage }}"$escape$,
