INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '043d7e5a-d071-4d93-acee-5bd9754fe42c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana $__rate_interval — Fix Your PromQL Queries Across Every Zoom Level$escape$,
  $escape$Hardcoding `[5m]` in PromQL range vectors silently breaks when users zoom into a 30-second window or pull 7 days of history. Grafana's `$__interval` macro computes the optimal step as `timeRange / maxDataPoints`, where `maxDataPoints` defaults to panel pixel width — but `$__interval` can shrink below your Prometheus scrape interval, producing "no data" gaps.

Use `$__rate_interval` instead. It's always `max(4 × scrape_interval, $__interval)`, guaranteeing enough samples for `rate()` and `increase()` regardless of zoom. Set `Min step` in the query editor (e.g., `15s`) to hard-floor the resolution without overriding `$__rate_interval`'s upper logic.

For variable-driven dashboards, combine this with a `$service` regex-match variable backed by a `label_values(up, job)` query so the interval adapts per-series automatically. In Loki metric queries, `$__interval` maps directly to the LogQL `step` parameter — `rate({app=~"$service"}[$__interval])` follows the same adaptive contract.

Avoid the `Resolution` 1/2x multiplier unless you're explicitly trading fidelity for query performance on wide ranges.$escape$,
  $escape$// Panel query — adaptive across any time range
sum by (status_code) (
  rate(
    http_requests_total{
      job=~"$service",
      namespace=~"$namespace"
    }[$__rate_interval]
  )
)

// Loki equivalent — same adaptive contract
sum by (level) (
  rate({app=~"$service"} | json [$__interval])
)$escape$,
  $escape$sql$escape$,
