INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'be5f3ec6-e6ed-4fa0-a798-74816a9b8372',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana Tempo — Distributed Tracing with Spans, Context Propagation, and Sampling$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana Tempo stores traces as flat, tag-based objects — no indexes, pure object storage. Each trace is a tree of spans linked by a shared `traceID` and parent `spanID`. When a request crosses service boundaries, trace context travels via W3C `traceparent` headers (or Zipkin B3); Tempo's OpenTelemetry Collector pipeline extracts these and stitches spans into a unified trace view in Grafana's Explore tab.

Sampling is where most teams bleed signal. Tempo supports both head-based sampling (decided at trace ingestion via the OTel Collector's `probabilistic_sampler`) and tail-based sampling via `tail_sampling` processor — the latter lets you keep 100% of error traces and 1% of success traces. Configure this in your Collector pipeline, not in the SDK.

Once traces land in Tempo, use TraceQL to slice them — `{ span.http.status_code = 500 && duration > 2s }` surfaces slow error spans directly. Wire Tempo as a data source in Grafana, then link it to your Loki logs and Prometheus metrics via Grafana's Correlations feature for full observability in a single pane.$escape$,
  $escape$# otel-collector-config.yaml — tail-based sampling for Tempo
processors:
  tail_sampling:
    decision_wait: 10s
    policies:
      - name: keep-errors
        type: status_code
        status_code: { status_codes: [ERROR] }
      - name: probabilistic-success
        type: probabilistic
        probabilistic: { sampling_percentage: 1 }

exporters:
  otlp:
    endpoint: tempo:4317
    tls:
      insecure: true

service:
  pipelines:
    traces:
      receivers: [otlp]
      processors: [tail_sampling]
      exporters: [otlp]$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
