INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'fe7f063e-2707-4efb-a442-0c7bcffeab3f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana vs Datadog — Replicating APM, Logs, and Synthetics Without the $23/Host Bill$escape$,
  $escape$Datadog's appeal is one-pane-of-glass: APM traces link to logs, synthetics trigger alerts, and everything correlates automatically. Grafana replicates this with Tempo (traces), Loki (logs), k6 (synthetics), and Prometheus (metrics) — but correlation is opt-in, not automatic.

The critical wiring is Loki's `derivedFields`: extract a `traceId` from log lines and Grafana renders a jump-to-Tempo link inline, mirroring Datadog's APM-to-log correlation. Without this config, your stack is four disconnected tools.

Datadog's synthetic monitors use a GUI-first model with global PoPs. Grafana k6 requires you to self-host or use k6 Cloud, but scripts are pure JS, version-controllable, and CI-native — `k6 run` in GitHub Actions beats Datadog's webhook triggers for shift-left testing.

Real trade-off: Datadog's cardinality limits (custom metrics cap at 100/host on standard plans) punish high-dimensionality label sets. Grafana Mimir + Prometheus has no such hard cap — your cost scales with storage, not instrumentation decisions. For teams burning >$5k/month on Datadog, the Grafana OSS stack with Grafana Cloud's free tier for alerting is a legitimate migration path.$escape$,
  $escape$# grafana/provisioning/datasources/loki.yaml
apiVersion: 1
datasources:
  - name: Loki
    type: loki
    url: http://loki:3100
    jsonData:
      derivedFields:
        - name: TraceID
          matcherRegex: 'traceId=(\w+)'
          url: '${__value.raw}'
          datasourceUid: tempo-uid  # Links directly into Tempo trace view
          urlDisplayLabel: 'Open in Tempo'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
