INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b6292f11-98e8-4a5f-b184-ca7acda3e77a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana SLOs — Turning Raw Metrics into Error Budgets and Burn Rate Alerts$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana's native SLO plugin (grafana-slo-app) converts a PromQL ratio into a full observability contract — SLI calculation, error budget tracking, and multi-window burn rate alerting — in one API call.

An SLI is a ratio metric: good_events / total_events expressed in PromQL. An SLO wraps it with a target and window (99.9% over 30 days). An SLA is the external commitment — typically 0.3–0.5% below your SLO to absorb incident response time.

Error budget = (1 − 0.999) × 43,200 min = 43.2 minutes/month. Grafana renders remaining budget on the auto-generated dashboard.

When you POST to the SLO API, Grafana provisions:
- Recording rules across five windows (5m, 30m, 1h, 2h, 6h)
- Multi-window burn rate alerts: fast burn (14.4× for 1h + 5m windows) and slow burn (1× for 6h + 30m windows)
- A pre-built burndown dashboard linked to the SLO

Burn rate = actual error rate ÷ error budget rate. A 14.4× rate exhausts the monthly budget in ~2 hours. The dual-window condition — both windows must breach simultaneously — is Grafana's mechanism to suppress transient spikes from paging on-call.$escape$,
  $escape$curl -X POST \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $GRAFANA_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  "$GRAFANA_URL/api/plugins/grafana-slo-app/resources/v1/slo" \
  -d '{
    "name": "api-availability",
    "objectives": [{"value": 0.999, "window": "30d"}],
    "indicator": {
      "ratio": {
        "successMetric": "http_requests_total{status!~\"5..\"}",
        "totalMetric": "http_requests_total"
      }
    }
  }'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
