INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0c221835-b1f5-4a81-928e-8046bdf2419a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana Health Checks — Liveness, Readiness, and Datasource Dependency Monitoring$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana exposes two native health endpoints out of the box. `GET /api/health` returns liveness state — JSON with `database`, `version`, and `commit`. If `database` is anything other than `"ok"`, Grafana is up but degraded. For readiness, pair this with `/healthz`, which returns HTTP 200 only when Grafana is fully initialized and ready to serve traffic — useful as a Kubernetes readiness probe.

For dependency health, use `GET /api/datasources/:id/health` (introduced in Grafana 9.0). This triggers each datasource's own health check — Prometheus scrapes, Loki connectivity, Postgres ping — and returns `status: ok | error` with a message. Automate this across all datasources via the Search API (`GET /api/datasources`) to build a dependency health sweep.

For uptime monitoring, scrape Grafana's built-in Prometheus metrics at `/metrics`. Track `grafana_datasource_request_duration_seconds` and `grafana_api_response_status_total` to alert on datasource latency regressions before users notice broken panels. Wire these into an alerting rule with a `for: 2m` hold to suppress transient blips.$escape$,
  $escape$#!/bin/bash
GRAFANA_URL="http://localhost:3000"
AUTH="admin:admin"

# Liveness
curl -sf "$GRAFANA_URL/api/health" | jq '.database'

# Readiness
curl -sf -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" "$GRAFANA_URL/healthz"

# Datasource dependency health sweep
curl -su "$AUTH" "$GRAFANA_URL/api/datasources" | \
  jq '.[].id' | \
  while read id; do
    echo "DS $id:"
    curl -su "$AUTH" "$GRAFANA_URL/api/datasources/$id/health" | jq '{status,message}'
  done$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
